<DOC><DOCNO> AP890722-0125 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 1841EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-22 0334</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0345</SECOND><HEAD>Showers And Storms Sweep Much of The Nation</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Thunderstorms rumbled across much of the nation on Saturday,sweeping through Arkansas, the lower Missouri Valley, the lowerGreat Lakes and the upper Ohio Valley.   A low pressure center in northeastern Missouri combined with acouple weak upper-level weather systems moving southeast acrossOklahoma to create showers and thunderstorms.   In Arkansas and the lower Missouri Valley, showers andthunderstorms were developing early Saturday afternoon.   Showers and thunderstorms moving along a warm front werescattered through the lower Great Lakes region and the upper OhioValley. The rain and storms also hit the southeastern UnitedStates, mainly along the Gulf Coast and the southern Atlantic Coast.   But the rest of the nation enjoyed dry weather, with clear skiesin the upper Mississippi Valley and the northwestern United States.   Heavier rainfall totals for the six-hour period ending at 2 p.m.EDT included 1 2@3 inches at Kirksville, Mo. The storms dumped upto 1 inch of rain Saturday morning throughout southern sections ofKansas City.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 55degrees at Arcata and Crescent City, Calif., to 106 degrees atChina Lake, Calif.   The low for the nation Saturday was 38 degrees at Baker, Ore.   Sunday's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstormsfrom the southern Plains to the lower Great Lakes and the southernand middle Atlantic Coast states, and from New Mexico and Arizonato western Montana; numerous showers and thunderstorms from theeastern and central Gulf Coast, in the middle Mississippi Valley,and in northern and central Arizona; and sunny skies throughout therest of the nation.   Sunday afternoon highs were forecast in the upper 80s and lower90s in the southern and middle Atlantic Coast region; above 90across much of Texas, much of the northern Plains and most of thewestern United States; above 100 degrees in the southwesterndeserts; and in the 70s along the Pacific Coast.</TEXT></DOC>